But movement may appear to be continuous, though it is not really so3 a succession of very short motions, interspersed with rests, will give us the feeling of continuity. As a fact, our senses often mislead us; as, for instance, in certain phenomena of sight, and in the vibrations of which sound consists. If the most rapid possible movement is at the rate of one point per instant, it follows that the world cannot be larges than it is; for if larger, it would revolve more rapidly, and that is im- possible: a confirmation of what has been proved elsewhere and other— wise (39, 42). — “But if the apices of several pyramids touched, they would be in the same place, and thus coi'ncide.” This is merely begging the question. If a point has position of its own, it cannot be in the same place with another. — lt is said that in Wyclif's system each point must touch an infinity of others; which leads to difficulties. ssut this is denied. Six points only touch a seventh placed in their midst. Thus in certain directions one cannot go immediately from one point to the next; their position follows certain fixed rules, somewhat like the grain in wood‚ or the lines of cleavage in crystals. A line drawn from one point to another which it cannot touch directly, only by means of a third, is nevertheless not bent; for it is as straight as a line can possibly be.
